<subsection xml:id="tkMathematicalModels"   xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title>Functions as Models</title>

<subsubsection xml:id="tkBasicProp"><title>Properties of the basic functions</title>

<p>The eight basic functions are often used as models.</p>

<p>For these Examples, refer to the eight basic functions:
    <md><mrow>f(x) \amp = x \amp   f(x) \amp = \abs{x}  \amp  f(x) \amp = x^2  \amp  f(x) \amp = x^3</mrow>
        <mrow>f(x) \amp = \sqrt{x}  \amp  f(x) \amp = \sqrt[3]{x}  \amp  f(x) \amp = \dfrac{1}{x} \amp   f(x) \amp = \dfrac{1}{x^2}</mrow></md></p>

<example><statement><p>Which of the eight basic functions are always increasing?</p></statement>

<solution><p><m>f(x)=x,~~~f(x)=x^3,~~~f(x)=\sqrt{x},~~~f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x}</m></p></solution></example>

<example><statement><p>Which of the eight basic functions are concave up for positive <m>x</m>?</p></statement>

<solution><p><m>f(x)=x^2,~~~f(x)=x^3,~~~f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x},~~~f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x^2}</m></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Which of the eight basic functions are undefined at <m>x=0</m>?</p></statement>
<answer><p><m>f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x},~~~f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x^2}</m></p></answer></exercise>

<exercise><statement><p>Which of the eight basic functions are always non-negative?</p></statement>
<answer><p><m>f(x)=\abs{x},~~~f(x)=x^2,~~~f(x)=\sqrt{x},~~~f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x^2}</m></p></answer></exercise>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="tkSimpAbsVal"><title>Simplify absolute value functions</title>

<p>The piecewise definition of the absolute value function is
    <me>f(x) =
        \begin{cases}
        x \amp  \text{if} ~~x\ge 0\\
        -x \amp  \text{if} ~~x\lt 0
        \end{cases}</me>
To write the absolute value of some other algebraic expression, we replace <m>x</m> by the expression wherever <m>x</m> appears.</p>

<example><statement><p>Simplify the function <m>~f(x)=|2x-8|~</m> as a piecewise defined function.</p></statement>

<solution><p>We use the definition of absolute value and replace <m>x</m> by <m>2x-8</m>.
    <me>f(x) =
        \begin{cases}
        2x-8 \amp  \text{if} ~~2x-8\ge 0\\
        -(2x-8)  \amp  \text{if} ~~2x-8\lt 0
        \end{cases}</me>
    Then we simplify each expression.
    <me>f(x) =
        \begin{cases}
        2x-8 \amp  \text{if} ~~x\ge 4\\
        8-2x  \amp  \text{if} ~~x\lt 4
        \end{cases}</me>
</p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Simplify the function <m>~f(x)=|6-3x|~</m> as a piecewise defined function.</p></statement>
    <answer><p><me>f(x) =
        \begin{cases}
        6-3x \amp  \text{if} ~~x\le 2\\
        3x-6  \amp  \text{if} ~~x\gt 2
        \end{cases}</me>
    </p></answer></exercise>

<exercise><statement><p>Simplify the function <m>~f(x)=|1+4x|~</m> as a piecewise defined function.</p></statement>
    <answer><p><me>f(x) =
        \begin{cases}
        1+4x \amp  \text{if} ~~x\ge \dfrac{-1}{4}\\
        -1-4x  \amp  \text{if} ~~x\lt \dfrac{-1}{4}
        \end{cases}</me>
    </p></answer></exercise>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="tkIntNot"><title>Use interval notation</title>

<p>Recall that square brackets on an interval mean that the endpoints are included, and round brackets mean that the endpoints are not included.</p>

<example><statement><p>Write each set with interval notation, and graph the set on a number line.
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>3 \le x \lt 6</m></li>
    <li><m>x \ge -9</m></li>
    <li><m>x \le 1~\text{or}~x\gt 4</m></li>
    <li><m>-8 \lt x \le 5~\text{or}~-1\le x \lt 3</m></li>
</ol></p></statement>
 
<solution><p><ol marker="a">
    <li><p><m>[3,6).</m> This is called a half-open or half-closed interval. <m>3</m> is included in the interval, but <m>6</m> is not included.</p>
    <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-1.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
    <li><p><m>[-9, \infty).</m> We use round brackets next to the symbol <m>\infty</m> because <m>\infty</m> is not a specific number and is not included in the set.</p>
    <image width="90%" source="images/fig-2-5-2.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
    <li><p><m>(-\infty,1] \cup (4, \infty).</m> The word “or” describes the union of two sets. The symbol <m>~\cup~</m> is used for union.</p>
    <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-3.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
    <li><p><m>(-8,-5] \cup [-1,3).</m></p>
    <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-4.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
</ol></p></solution></example>

<exercise><statement><p>Write each set with interval notation, and graph the set on a number line.
<ol marker="a" cols="2">
    <li><m>-5 \lt x \le 3</m></li>
    <li><m>-6 \lt x \lt \infty</m></li>
    <li><m>x \lt -3 ~\text{or}~ x\ge -1</m></li>
    <li><m>-6 \le x \lt-4 ~\text{or}~ -2 \lt x \le 0</m></li></ol></p></statement>
<answer><p><ol marker="a">
        <li><p><m>(-5,-3]</m></p>
            <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-5.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
        <li><p><m>(-6, \infty)</m></p>
            <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-6.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
        <li><p><m>(-\infty,-3) \cup [-1,\infty)</m></p>
            <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-7.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
        <li><p><m>[-6,-4) \cup (-2,0]</m></p>
            <image width="70%" source="images/fig-2-5-8.png"><description>interval</description></image></li>
</ol></p></answer></exercise>
</subsubsection>









